&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Fire ritual is found in many ancient religions. Unlike the\n&gt; elements of earth, water and air, fire is ever pure and it purifies\n&gt; whatever it comes in contact with. The Sanskrit name for fire is\n&gt; paavaka, i.e. purifier. Fire is a living god that everyone has access\n&gt; to. Spending time worshipping god through fire purifies one&#39;s subtle\n&gt; consciousness. Homam is far more effective than most other sadhanas in\n&gt; improving one&#39;s focus, changing one&#39;s inner personality and removing\n&gt; material and spiritual obstacles. One need not take my words for\n&gt; granted. One can try for oneself for a few months. The proof of the\n&gt; pudding is in eating it.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Vedic seers (rishis) performed homam regularly, for the\n&gt; benefit of the world. When composing the Jyotish masterpiece &quot;Brihat\n&gt; Paaraasara Horaa Saastram&quot; just before the advent of Kali yuga, for\n&gt; guidance to the people of Kali yuga, Maharshi Parasara recommended\n&gt; various types of homam as remedial measures for various problems in the\n&gt; horoscope. In fact, most remedies he recommended involve homam. Parasara\n&gt; asked to follow whatever procedures one was taught for starting fire and\n&gt; did not focus on the nitty gritty of homam. He only gave the main mantra\n&gt; to beused in homam. Parasara&#39;s clear teachings set to rest the notion\n&gt; that some people have, that homam is not for Kali yuga.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; * * *\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; In Bhagavad Gita, Sri Krishna said, &quot;yaGYaanaaM\n&gt; japayaGYo.asmi&quot;, i.e. I am japa among all sacrifices. Some people use\n&gt; this line to suggest that japam (meditation) is superior to homa/yajna.\n&gt; Let me put that in perspective.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; In the line just above that line, Sri Krishna also said, &quot;I am\n&gt; Om among all mantras&quot;. However, do we only meditate with the supreme\n&gt; mantra &quot;Om&quot; and leave all other mantras?\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; If one says that sitting on the pinnacle is the best part of\n&gt; climbing a mountain, it does not mean that the process of climbing it\n&gt; using various kinds of gear is useless. In fact, one needs that process\n&gt; to reach the pinnacle. Most cannot reach the pinnacle directly.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Similarly, Om is the supreme of all mantras being the source\n&gt; of all, but reaching the source may require using several mantras first\n&gt; to purify oneself. Meditating and absorbing consciousness in the Supreme\n&gt; (japa) may be the supreme sacrifice, but it may require purification and\n&gt; preparation by engaging in other kinds of sacrifices (hama/yajna).\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; When one does homam or yajna, one is engaging in external\n&gt; actions and one is unlikely to reach samadhi (absorbption in the\n&gt; Supreme). When a perfectly purified person does japam (i.e. sits still\n&gt; and contemplates), one may reach samadhi. However, to purify oneself,\n&gt; homam is far more effective.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; * * *\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Detailed manuals giving short procedures for doing various\n&gt; types of homam by oneself are available on the website given below. You\n&gt; can use the resources on that website to perform several kinds of short\n&gt; homam by yourself.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; Now *hundreds* of people are performing homam by themselves\n&gt; either daily or weekly. Some people are also doing monthly.\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt;\n&gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; &gt; When Manish (my s